  _push(`<div${ssrRenderAttrs(_attrs)}> La Vista Part One: Prologue I hope I know what I&#39;m getting myself into. Not regarding Panama or development, but with this blogging, vlogging stuff. I know things are going to get busy, but I feel like this project is too important to miss capturing it all. I hope you enjoy reading, I tend to get pretty wordy. There will likely be way too many pictures and videos as well. I might even dump raw video content on here from time to time. B-roll type stuff that no-one wants to see. Because I film so much, I often capture rare moments, interesting creatures or events. This tends to be pretty awesome and worth seeing in my opinion, but I don&#39;t have the time right now to sift through it all and cut out the boring stuff, so if you want to see cool things sometimes happen it might involve sitting through too much B-roll. I&#39;ll try to at least add music or a disclaimer, but I might not even mess with audio... which also means you might hear me drop some foul language, talk about something political, etc. If you are easily offended or bothered by this sort of thing, try to stick to the main content, which I will strive to keep within the realm of what most people are comfortable with. A View (Vista) of the First Month Let&#39;s begin at the beginning then, shall we? NO! To get to the beginning, we must first develop some background. Hah. Told you this would be wordy. Months before departing for Panama, Ashley and I sat on the couch of our apartment in the beautiful city of Cape Coral, Florida. We had been researching real estate development, property management, and a world of other subjects for oh, I don&#39;t know, the past few years. We fell in love with the work at the ripe old age of (early twenties I guess?), and had completed a few projects at this point. We were in the final stages of our condo conversion project at Pine Key, and about to begin the development of townhomes. I make this sound like Ash and I deserve too much credit, none of our involvement with Pine Key would have been possible if it weren&#39;t for our a close friendship with someone who&#39;s name I haven&#39;t asked permission to release. As we looked at the market and where we believed it was headed, and we discussed our options. Ash and I felt that it was an excellent time for us to go boldly forth on a project of entirely our own design. After all, I had been designing mock communities based around sustainable practices in tropical to subtropical climates. Why not see if we can make the vision a reality? So we got to work. The first priority was to determine a location. At first, we were honestly looking at Florida. There are quite a few advantages to Florida, despite a few &#39;yee-haw&#39; characters that make silly sounding news headlines. Truthfully, we spent a great deal of time reaching out to landowners across the state, narrowing down our best options and making arrangements. We watched as prices fell across the nation each day, and few of our tracked properties were making it to closing. We opted to take our time. Each day spent expanding our view of the market, was met with further reductions in price. Timing the bottom seems actually quite an easy task when you track over a hundred homes on Zillow in a spreadsheet that you update daily. Easy. As the search parameters continued to expand, we looked at states all across the sub-tropical portions of the US. Then we even pushed our view up to Appalachia and out across the plains. We started making preliminary arrangements for seller financed deals all over the country. Well mostly, I wasn&#39;t super actively looking in the west due to insanely inflated price-tags. Sticks and stones are only worth so much guys, and your dirt is mostly desert so the whole land-value thing doesn&#39;t really do it for me. The plan was to pick up as many viable seller-financed deals as we could. We were predominantly looking for rural/semi-rural/suburban single-family homes that fell under a bunch of our metric requirements. We had a plan to operate some as rentals, some as rehab-to rentals, and some as fix-and-flip deals. All were projects to be managed by us directly, and we were gearing up to do some serious traveling, likely living out of suitcases. Oh yeah. Project time. I&#39;m gonna put some video content here eventually. Just uh... think happy thoughts for now, and look at this picture. Now that all sounds pretty damn exciting to me, but I know some of you (Mom) are probably thinking, &quot;How could you drag your family all over like that for an indefinite period of time, that&#39;s irresponsible, unsafe, etc. etc.&quot; Well, that&#39;s your opinion. It&#39;s fine to have wrong opinions, and you are welcome to voice your concerns, even when they are wrong. For those of you that don&#39;t know, our son Parker is home-schooled. Since COVID, Parker has been coming to work with us - whether that&#39;s at home, or out and about. We give him schoolwork throughout the day, as well as video games, (too much) YouTube, and typically end his day with an aggressive curriculum that challenges him without discouraging or overwhelming. Yeah, we&#39;ve pretty much got this parenting thing down at this point. Humility however, I could work on. Of course things will change as he grows, hopefully we continue to adapt, but overall I&#39;d say that at this point, his education is going very well, despite being unconventional. Don&#39;t even get me started on what he picks up from working with us. Not only do we get plenty of quality time as a family, but he gets early insight into our careers, and adult life in general. So really, moving to Panama wasn&#39;t even very disruptive for Parker, with the exception of the addition of Spanish lessons to his education. Ashley was a little tense about it at first, but she quickly came around and was proclaiming her love of Panama within a week of arrival. Departure Alright, back to the apartment. There we were, discussing our options, when we realized that we shouldn&#39;t limit ourselves to the US. If we were willing to look at properties all the way up in Arkansas (seriously we were this close to closing a deal in Arkansas), then why not look internationally as well? That way we can at least satisfy the condition of tropical/sub-tropical climate, and who knows what other opportunities could be out there. Due diligence can mean a lot of things to a lot of people, but it&#39;s something I tend to obsess over. Spreadsheets have always held a soft-spot in my heart, and there&#39;s nothing more satisfying to me than taking all the quantifiable parameters that influence a given topic and analyze the hell out of them. Putting together a list of possible countries was easy enough. The Koppen climate classification was readily available on wikipedia, so finding all my tropical options was a piece of cake. From there it was just a matter of gathering every possible relevant metric, every significant slice of data I could get my hands on, then determining which country checked the most boxes. Can&#39;t move somewhere with high crime rates, really looking for something with clear economic growth, clickity-clack, beepity-boop, all the shiny green rectangles in excel revealed these three top picks: Panama, Costa Rica, and Puerto Rico. Skip past additional weeks of research, and I was all set to move to Puerto Rico. Wait what? I thought Panama was the choice. At the time, I was still stuck in my comfort zone. Puerto Rico seemed like an easy way to stay ~somewhat~ in the US, while being a pretty killer option from a business standpoint. I mean come on, what real estate developer doesn&#39;t want to avoid paying income taxes, and property gains taxes on properties sold within AND outside of the territory. That deal in Arkansas was still looking pretty good, and plane tickets to and from Puerto Rico were affordable enough we could still self-manage with the right tenants. We had most of our belongings packed at this point, and were once again this close to pulling the trigger and buying plane tickets to Puerto Rico, once again with a seller-financed deal ready and waiting for when we landed. But we had this bright idea. Since there was a hurricane coming, and we had a family reunion already scheduled later that month, we decided it would be a good idea to make a quick stop in Utah to catch up with all the extended family and friends that we could. It had been quite a few years since either of us had seen many people from our extended family, and we figured it would be a while longer still after we move to a distant US territory. So we did, finally, book some freaking plane tickets. And those plane tickets were scheduled for... the day after we made the decision to go. Quick phone call to Mom and Dad to make sure they were cool with us crashing at their place for a few weeks before the family reunion, and it was crunch time. We stayed up all night packing our things, what we were bringing, and trying to finish packing our belongings. At this point, we had a moving company scheduled to come pick up our stuff and take it to Puerto Rico. Yes, we were all in on Puerto Rico. I kept trying to convince them to subcontract with someone to get our stuff at least packed up and in their local storage facility before that hurricane, but they kept telling me not to worry about it. With the help of my sister Amberly, we were able to make it to the airport in time. I forgot my wallet in the car, but Ashley had my ID by some miracle, or foresight, or both. Amberly tried to run to the car to bring it to us before we got through security, but it was too late. Oh well, we can have her mail it to us later. Oof, forgetting my wallet in the car ends up being the most regrettable thing I&#39;ve done in at least a week. Anyway, fast forward past the drug sniffing dog that definitely was not trained to hit on cannabis, and we made it to the terminal literally just as the last call was being made for our flight. We did it. If you made it to this point, you truly must give a shit about my life. We should talk more. Come visit me. Touchdown in Utah Ugh, there&#39;s more? Yeah I know, wordy. But here&#39;s the thing, there&#39;s a lot going on in my life, so there are a lot of words. We made it to Utah, sleep deprived but excited. We planned ahead to ride the Trax down from the airport to Daybreak, and then my mom was going to pick us up from there. I rode the trains a lot as a kid, and wanted to give Parker the experience. Plus Ash and I rode the trains together a bit as well, so the nostalgia value made it a great time. We then began planning almost every hour of every day of our stay, in order to maximize the number of people we could see. We did our best, but we didn&#39;t see enough of you. Seriously come visit, especially if I didn&#39;t get to see you while in town. Ashley&#39;s mom April was super generous and gave us free use of her car while we were in town, so we were really able to make the most out of our time. Again, wasn&#39;t enough, but I&#39;m really glad I got to see those of you that I did. Additional time at night was spent organizing our move to Puerto Rico, and coordinating with friends and family regarding the hurricane - which was by this point expected to hit our area. Projections were showing that it was going to be a big one, and our neighborhood landed in an evacuation zone. We had left quite a few survival supplies and other useful things, so we were able to share what we had left and do some good. The moving company obviously cancelled, which really sucked and threw off all the related pre-arranged things we had lined up to happen. We ended up relying largely on Ashley&#39;s brother Joe to manage the move, and we are really grateful for all the work he did to make sure our stuff ended up either sold or in storage. Finally, time to breathe, on our fun-filled family reunion aboard the Carnival Panorama Cruise Ship!!! As Usual, Things Weren&#39;t That Easy Neither Ashley or I had left the country before, and we didn&#39;t have passports. Around this time, we had also been talking to multiple natives, current, and past residents of Puerto Rico. Turns out, Puerto Rico looked a lot better on paper than the boots on the ground view. Especially in light of a recent hurricane that hit, and after further discussion with firsthand-sources regarding Panama and Costa Rica, we pivoted. Hard. Last minute research was crammed, sleep was a distant memory, and we came to the decision that, although both Panama and Costa Rica appeared to be very competitive options, Panama would be the winning choice. As a bonus, the country lies outside of the Hurricane Belt that we had quickly come to grow tired of dealing with. After a trip to the passport office in Salt Lake, we were informed that our passports would take 4-8 weeks to process. Time we did not have. Alternatively, we could go to the nearest printing office in Los Angeles and get it done same-day as long as we scheduled an appointment. Luckily, our cruise left from the port just south of LA, and we already had plane tickets booked to go there. After a quick phone call to the US Department of travel (that&#39;s a joke, nothing about our government is ever quick), we were informed that we would not be able to schedule an appointment until after the our cruise. Surprisingly, that wasn&#39;t as big a setback as you would think. The cruise line didn&#39;t require us to have passports at all, they required enough identification on their own that Mexico is cool with them doing their own thing. With a plan to get our passports after the cruise, we packed our things once more and fly to LA. Which is by far the worst city I&#39;ve ever been to, but they do have some cool museums, pretty (but cold) beaches, and some guy I met on a bus referred to it as the &#39;Mecca of weed&#39; so I suppose it has some advantages. Truthfully, the city of Los Angeles had me pretty depressed for a bit. As usual we tried to really get out there and talk to people from all walks of life. I don&#39;t really want to go too much into details, but from what we experienced in the couple of weeks we were there, it wasn&#39;t a very happy place. Not a problem I could solve, couldn&#39;t get out of there fast enough. Luckily, we did just that! All aboard the Carnival Panorama. We spent most of the day in lines, but luckily a good portion of that time was spent catching up with family. Man, if there&#39;s one thing this cruise affirmed for me, it&#39;s that I have a great family. So many good people. Can&#39;t believe how much everyone has grown up since we&#39;ve been away. Here&#39;s a couple galleries of pictures from the occasion. Truly this was an awesome vacation, and a great way to leave the country for the first time, and a spectacular way to spend time with family. The Fun Times Were Gone Too Quickly Yet again, I felt like I didn&#39;t get enough time with everyone. Wish I could have had more. I don&#39;t know how many times I&#39;ve gotta say it, but all of you should definitely come visit. After a week of cruising around the western coast of Mexico, we were back in Los Angeles and saying our goodbyes. I hate goodbyes. Next was our appointment with big brother, who apparently really can make work happen same-day if you pay them enough. Typical government, things only go smoothly when you pay them off. Off we went, on a 36 hr adventure from airport to airport. This time, while sick. All of us had caught a bit of a cold, and apparently quite a few members of the extended family were in similar shape. I remember hitting the tylenol pretty hard, and falling asleep on airport floors where possible. Ash and Parker were each a runny-nosed mess, and we were all pretty much miserable. We had a long enough layover in Vegas to warrant a hotel stay, so we found a $20 room in the stratosphere, grabbed some McDonald&#39;s from the floor below ours, and slept hard. It made all the difference in the world, and we were all in better shape for the last leg of our journey. Bienvenidos a Panama City Once again, things couldn&#39;t be easy. Customs or security or whoever is in charge of letting us out the front door stopped us and took us to a back office. No it&#39;s not what you think, they were fine with that. I was traveling with cash (there isn&#39;t a Chase Bank in Panama). Apparently, you have to know the exact dollar amount of cash you have, and they made me go count it out in the bathroom on the floor. Not a fun thing to do at 3am. Oh and noone spoke English. The airport was literally empty, our flight was the last one coming in for the night and we were the last people to leave. So anyway, I finish counting a bunch of ones in the bathroom, and I go back in and fill out my form without a translator since they don&#39;t allow you to use your phone in the back office, and they take me to a further back office, that has a freaking counting machine. Where was that five minutes ago. So they count it all up, and my number doesn&#39;t match, and me and this lady I don&#39;t understand go back and forth in my novice level Spanish, and eventually after she finishes threatening to detain me, I fill out another form with the correct number, and we are able to finally leave. For some reason, there were still taxis outside at like 4am, so we were able to get a cheap ride to our first stop. Hotel Acapulco, located in the heart of Panama City. </div>`);
